node.accessibility_caption: Photo by MIT on September 10, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and outdoors.

node.text:
Walking around the MIT campus, you might come across a plaque marking Danny Lewin Square at the corner of Main and Vassar Streets. The honor commemorates Danny Lewin SM ’98, who was one of nearly 3,000 people who died in the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001. Lewin was killed onboard American Airlines Flight 11, and is credited with trying to stop the plane from crashing into the World Trade Center. Although his life was cut short at 31, Lewin made an indelible mark on the field of computer science. He was co-founder of Akamai Technologies and a doctoral candidate at MIT at the time of his death. 

In 2017, Lewin and his Akamai cofounder, MIT Professor Tom Leighton, were inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame for applying algorithms to solve web congestion. “He was a very, very bright fellow, and a great leader, inspirational fellow, and really a unique human being,” Leighton told MIT News in 2011. “Anyone that extraordinary when they’re lost you never replace that.”

Read more about how Daniel Lewin transformed the Internet, see link in profile.

#911 #WorldTradeCenter #ComputerScience #inventor #algorithms #NIHF @inventorshof @mitalumni

node.text:
To celebrate our 50th anniversary, @mitmuseum be sharing 50 posts over the next 50 days starting with a look back at key moments and milestones, then turning to look forward as we make plans to open a new museum in 2022. 

Join us as we reminisce and reimagine, and share your own memories and hopes for the future at #MITMuseum50

Reposted from @mitmuseum

#MITMuseum #ThisisMIT #LookingBack #TBT
___

node.text:
Breaking News! On Sept. 5, 2021, for the first time, a large high-temperature superconducting electromagnet was ramped up to a field strength of 20 tesla, the most powerful magnetic field of its kind ever created on Earth. That successful demonstration helps resolve the greatest uncertainty in the quest to build the world’s first fusion power plant that can produce more power than it consumes, according to the project’s leaders at MIT and startup company Commonwealth Fusion Systems. Read about the research, see link in profile.

Jordan Harrod is leaning against a green metal fence along the Charles River. She has one elbow on the fence and one hand on her hip.

node.text:
A researcher, writer, policy advocate, and YouTuber, Jordan Harrod is dedicated to communicating science. The HST doctoral student uses machine learning as a tool for studying pain and consciousness — and as subject matter for her popular videos. “I didn’t come into graduate school with a neuroscience background, so every day is an opportunity to learn new things about the brain. Even after three years, I’m still amazed with how much we have yet to discover.” Read about Jordan's journey, see link in profile.

Image: Adam Glanzman

#neuroscience #science #communications #consciousness #writer #BrainResearch #PolicyAdvocate #MachineLearning #HealthSciences #YouTuber
@mit_picower @mit_bcs

node.text:
#FlashbackFriday @MechE alum Ruth Heffernan Marsh ’85 is pictured above in this awesome photo as she races along the Charles during a regatta in her freshman year. Marsh—a member of the MIT sailing team for a year before switching to cross-country—recalls fond memories as part of the MIT sailing team:

“I can’t remember how well I or the team did on the day this photo was taken, but I do recall the team doing well that season. I have very fond memories of that fall—I loved the boathouse, the coaches, the camaraderie between the men’s and women’s teams. It was a place where I felt instantly comfortable and had some mastery while I was figuring out the whole MIT scene, which I found fairly intimidating that first year."

Repost @mit_engineering
Original source: @mitalumni Tech Reflection

node.accessibility_caption: Biology student Patricia Pujols is seated in a lab with mentor Ellen Guss, a doctoral student in Professor Troy Littleton's lab. Both wearing masks.

node.text:
A pivot from accounting to neuroscience: Through a summer research program at MIT, Patricia Pujols (seated) explored the neuromuscular junction, and a future in science. At MIT, Pujols says, “I stepped out of my comfort zone and strengthened my skills. MSRP gave me all the tools I needed to have an enriching experience in science, as well as the opportunity to meet colleagues that I will remember for the rest of my life.” Read about Patricia's journey, see link in profile.

Photo: Mandana Sassanfar
